column5:
1. Poor predictors of survival in debility and adult failure to thrive that could warrant referral to hospice
   1. recurrent or intractable infections such as pneumonia, urinary tract infection, or sepsis;
   2. progressive weight loss of > 10% in the last 6 months;
   3. dysphagia with recurrent aspiration or inadequate oral intake;
   4. progressive deep ulcerations
2. hospice criteria for adult failure to thrive
   1.  Karnofsky or Palliative Performance Scale value less than or equal to 40%
   2. BMI <22

1. Lorazepam, 0.5–2.0mg po/SL, against the buccal mucosa until settled, then dosed routinely q 4–6 h to keep settled
2. Lorazepam 0.5 to 1.0 mg SQ/IV q 1 h prn until settled, then dosed routinely q 4–6 h to keep settled
3. Diazepam, 5–10mg po, IV q 1 h until settled, then dosed routinely q 6–8 h prn;
4. Clonazepam, 0.25–2.0mg po q 12 h;
5. Midazolam, 0.5mg IV q 15 min until settled, then by continuous SC or IV infusion.

1. Improved survival in persistent vegetative state;
2. Life prolongation in extreme short gut syndrome;
3. Improved survival in acute-phase brain injury or stroke;
4. Improved quality of life and survival in amyotrophic lateral sclerosis; x improved survival in short-term critical care patients.
